      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <!-- 
Encoded for Siddham by Eszter Somogyi, following Ramesh and Tewari's edition unless otherwise noted in comments. Version of January 2019. Comments below by Dániel Balogh are offered "as is" and do not represent a thoroughly researched or considered opinion. 
-->
        <p><lb n="1"/>valkhāḥ paramabhaṭṭāraka-pādānuddhyāto mahārāja-svāmidāsaḥ samājñāpayati
<lb n="2"/>sarvvān evāsmat-santakān āyuktakān
</p>
        <p>vijñātam astu vaḥ samanujānīma Eṣā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>
<lb n="3"/>nānā-gotra-vrata-caraṇa-tapaḥ-svāddhyāyopetānāṁ valkh<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice>-vāstavyāryya-cāturvvaidya-
<lb n="4"/>pādānān narmmadāpara-kūle Udumbaragarttā-pathake mandara-pratyaya<sic>n</sic> damanānaka-
<lb n="5"/>grāmaṁ brahmadeya-krameṇa śāśvatam ācandrā<sic>rk</sic>a-tārakā-kālīna<surplus>ṁ</surplus>m anvaya-bho<lb break="no" n="6"/>
jyam a-cāṭa-bhaṭa-prāveśyaṁ bhogāyaivam idānīm eṣām asmābhiḥ kr̥tānujñā<lb break="no" n="7"/>
tam ucitayā brahmadeya-bhuktyā bhuñjatāṁ samāvāsayat<unclear>ā</unclear><choice>
            <sic>ś</sic>
            <corr>ñ</corr>
          </choice> ca sarvvair evāsma<!-- 
L7. RT read samāvāsayataś ca, emending to samāśvāsayatāṁś ca, which is agrammatical. I think the intent was °tāñ ca; tā is probably what is actually engraved, but the top part of the ligature does look more like ś than ñ. 
--><lb break="no" n="8"/>
t-pakṣa tat-kulīnārakṣika-preṣaṇika-bhaṭa-cchatrādibhiḥ samanumantavyam iti</p>
        <p><lb n="9"/>samukhaṁ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> varṣe <num value="63"><g type="numeral">60</g> 3</num> kārttika ba <num value="8">8</num><!-- 
L9 RT: samukham, Karttika. 
--></p>
        <ab><lb n="01"/>mahārāja-svāmidāsasya<!-- 
L margin.1 is engraved on the left margin, bottom to top, characters rotated 90° counterclockwise. 
--></ab>
